  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Tony&apos;s Chocolonely CLMRS: Growing, scaling and learning</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project aims to take the next steps in addressing child labour in the Tony&#x2019;s Chocolonely supply chain and in the wider sector and in proving the effectiveness and business case for our approach to child labour in the cocoa value chain. As Tony&#x2019;s Chocolonely continues to grow, we need our CLMRS to grow with us, to be future-proof, and to demonstrate that it is a viable model at a larger scale. We expect to add two new cooperatives each year, targeting an additional 2,000 farmers annually, and increasing our impact through our Five Sourcing Principles. The more beans we source, the more premium we pay to coops and their members, and the more cases of child labour we can find and remediate. We need to prove that it is possible to be a profitable company while implementing our approach and covering 100% of our supply chain with the child protection of the CLMRS. As part of this project, the CLMRS will be continued and improved at current (growing) cooperatives and rolled out at new cooperatives annually. A particular focus will be paid to ensuring a gender-sensitive approach to the CLMRS, with more women recruited to engage in monitoring and reaching more women with income generating activities. Efforts will also be made to increase the empowerment of women at coop and community level. Remediation of child labour cases has been a challenge in our CLMRS implementation, and through this project we will focus efforts on increasing the speed and effectiveness of remediation activities, and document and publish research on the most (cost) effective approaches. Finally, it is central to Tony&#x2019;s strategy to inspire others in the cocoa sector to act, and we will also conduct an external verification of our entire Five Sourcing Principles approach, with a particular focus on how our approach to the CLMRS is replicable, scalable and affordable.Addressing the root causesDue to our intensive monitoring (via the CLMRS) and ongoing collaboration with the International Cocoa Initiative, Tony&#x2019;s maintains a clear view on the risks and root causes of child labour in our supply chain. In 2021 we also implemented both an extensive needs assessment and the annual multi-dimensional poverty index study. The NORC report and the ILO Child Labour Global Estimates are also key sources.Our data and international research confirm that poverty is the primary cause of child labour. It is both a symptom and a cause of children engaging in labour. By paying farmers a fair price, ensuring thorough monitoring and rapid remediation of cases, empowering women, supporting community development projects focusing on education and health, and enabling the professionalisation of partner cooperatives, we seek to alleviate poverty in the communities where we source cocoa. Investments in education are also critical in addressing the cycle of poverty. We also raise awareness on child labour, in the recognition that a lack of understanding of what is and what isn&#x2019;t considered child labour can be considered a root cause. ApproachWe implement the CLMRS at all partner cooperatives. We also implement the 100WEEKS programme (unconditional cash transfers and VSLAs) at a third of our cooperatives. Farmer coaching, community-based awareness raising on child labour, and cooperative professional development with our partner TechnoServe are among our complementary interventions.</narrative>
  </description>
